<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / The Maastricht Vote: Lib Dems turn fire on Labour's 'night
of fun'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR PADDY ASHDOWN launched a fierce attack on Labour last night, accusing the
party of 'discreditable opportunism' for opposing the government motion. He
promised to support Maastricht's early ratification - not to back the
government's but Britain's future in Europe.
The Liberal Democrat leader warned that 'the cost of one night's fun for
Labour' could be tens of thousands of lost jobs. Delaying the treaty's
ratification would damage economic confidence and stem inward investment.
Amid repeated heckling by Labour MPs furious at his party's decision to back
the government motion, Mr Ashdown derided as 'legalistic analysis', the
claim of Mr John Smith, Labour leader, that the motion was one of confidence
in the government.
'If the government loses this debate tonight, will there be a general
election tomorrow? The answer is No. There will be a vote of confidence
tomorrow which the government will win because turkeys don't vote for
Christmas.
'Then on Friday morning we will wake up without a general election and with
Britain's future in Europe desperately damaged,' Mr Ashdown said.
If would not make any difference if the Commons forced Mr Major to resign to
be replaced by Mr Kenneth Clarke, home secretary - but the economic
consequences for Britain would be far graver.
If the debate had been a genuine opportunity to remove the government from
office, he said, Liberal Democrats would not have missed the chance.
Mr Ashdown said Maastricht was not perfect. He regretted the 'opt-outs' on
the social chapter and on economic and monetary union. But unless the
treaty's ratification was allowed to proceed, any future, more pro-European
government would not be able to re-instate those parts, he said.
Mr Ashdown did not receive support from other minor parties. Mr Seamus
Mallon, deputy leader of Northern Ireland's Social Democratic and Labour
party, signalled that he did not believe the motion was entirely about the
Maastricht treaty.
Although his party backs the treaty, the Commons was not been given a chance
to debate it 'on its merits', he said.
