<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / Labour threat on Sunday trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Labour party has threatened to oppose any proposals the government makes
for the reform of Sunday trading laws in England and Wales if the wages
councils are abolished.
The government is expected to make a statement on Sunday trading shortly,
and will need the support of Labour MPs to ensure that any reform passes
through the Commons. Many Conservative MPs oppose the extension of Sunday
trading on religious grounds.
The Employment Department has said that it sees 'no permanent place' for
wages councils, which set minimum rates for about 10 per cent of the working
population. There has been speculation that Mrs Gillian Shephard, the
employment secretary, will include their abolition in the Employment Bill,
which is likely to be published tomorrow.
The link between Labour's support for reform and wages councils emerged
during an information-seeking meeting between Ms Joan Ruddock, Labour's
spokesperson on Sunday trading and Mr Peter Lloyd, a junior home office
minister.
Ms Ruddock said the abolition of wages councils would undermine legal
guarantees of protection for retail workers - for example the provision that
Sunday working must be voluntary - which are central to Labour's support.
The unions argue that if wages councils were abolished there would be a
general downward pressure on pay that would depress premiums for Sunday
working particularly. Wages councils would be their preferred vehicle for
setting and policing such premium rates.
Both Labour and the government are committed to a free vote on Sunday
trading, but the Labour front bench will issue guidance on the reforms that
will strongly influence shadow ministers and many backbenchers.
The government has been committed to reform the Sunday trading laws since
1987 but has been reluctant to legislate after its last attempt was defeated
by a Conservative backbench rebellion in 1986.
The options are expected to range from full deregulation on the Scottish
model to a tightening of existing laws along the lines advocated by the Keep
Sunday Special campaign.
Pressure on the government to introduce urgent reform of Sunday trading laws
increased after the European Court of Justice suggested that it was up to
English courts to end the confusion surrounding the present legislation.
</TEXT>
