<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / Fresh threat for north-east pit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COAL has linked the survival chances of the only deep-coal colliery
in north-east England not on British Coal's recent 31-pit closure list to an
application for opencast coal extraction.
Ellington Colliery - or Big E - on the Northumberland coast near Ashington,
provides 1,600 mining jobs and sustains hundreds more by supplying coal to
the nearby Alcan aluminium smelter and Blyth power station.
The licence under which the pit tips 670,000 tonnes a year of unsightly
colliery waste on adjacent Lynemouth beach was renewed in 1990 on condition
that British Coal pursued other means of disposal before the licence expires
in mid 1995. It was warned that the licence would not be renewed unless the
planning system showed that no land-based alternative existed.
British Coal has told Northumberland County Council and local MPs that it
will submit a planning application next year seeking permission to dispose
of the waste on land next to the pit - and to mine 1.75m tonnes of coal
opencast over six years.
'Without a shadow of doubt it will be an extremely contentious application,'
said Mr Kevin Flaherty, the council's planning committee chairman,
yesterday. 'We do feel caught in the middle; there's a great deal of
pressure from both sides.'
British Coal says the proposal is 'absolutely crucial' for the pit's future.
Opencasting, it said, would create space for the waste. The site would avoid
environmentally unacceptable waste transported by road, avoiding extra costs
that would increase production overheads.
Northumberland County Council has protested that opencasting in the county,
providing 15 per cent of the UK's opencast coal, has reached unacceptable
levels.
The North East Opencast Action Group will oppose the application, said Mr
Andrew Pratt, the organisation's chairman. 'We think it's trying to hold a
gun to the county council's head,' he added.
Mr Jack Thompson, the National Union of Mineworkers-sponsored Labour MP for
adjacent Wansbeck, where most Ellington miners live, said he hoped the
council would oppose the plan. He added: 'It smells a little bit of
blackmail.'
</TEXT>
