<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / Inland Revenue changes tax relief eligibility on Lautro
levies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LEVIES imposed on life insurance companies under the terms of the Lautro
investor compensation and indemnity schemes will be eligible for tax relief,
the Inland Revenue has ruled.
Lautro is the Life Assurance and Unit Trust Regulatory Organisation, the
industry regulator.
In an extra-statutory concession, the Inland Revenue said contributions
through the Lautro investors' compensation scheme could be treated as a
management expense.
Separately, the Inland Revenue said regulations were laid before the Commons
this week to allow relief under the Lautro indemnity scheme.
Relief will be available for levies paid at any time since the scheme was
set up.
The investors' compensation scheme requires levies from life insurers under
the provisions of the 1986 Financial Services Act. It can treat the levy as
a management expense, which makes it eligible for tax relief.
Other life insurance company contributions to the investors' compensation
scheme, which are not imposed under the terms of the scheme, do not qualify
for tax relief.
However, under the new concession, contributions paid under the rules of a
Lautro imposed levy introduced in December last year can now be treated as
expenses of management.
The compensation scheme, which was established in 1988, provides
compensation to investors for otherwise unrecoverable losses.
The costs of compensation are allocable under the rules between the members
of the various self-regulating organisations and bodies regulated directly
by the Securities and Investments Board.
The regulations allowing tax relief on Lautro indemnity levies extend the
concessions already available under the 1975 Policyholders Protection Act
and the Investments Board scheme created by the 1986 Financial Services Act.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
