<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / Executives land in back seats with air-fare curb
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS TRAVELLERS are getting a taste of life at the back of the aircraft
as companies cut their spending on air fares in the struggle to control
costs, according to a survey by Mori for the Wagons-lits travel group.
But many senior executives have held on to their travel privileges - and
they rarely come back with gifts for the secretaries who book their flights
and hotels.
Nearly half the 400 senior executives and secretaries surveyed said their
companies were instructing travellers to use cheaper hotels and flights.
One traveller complained about 'the party of ball-bearing salesmen who are
always checking in in front of me'. Another said: 'I am dying to find out
what anything other than baggage class is like on any aeroplane.'
Some companies did their best to soften the blow. A senior executive said:
'We amended our air travel policy - except if you had a bad back, then you
could still be in first. We had an amazing number of people with a bad
back.'
About 30 per cent of businesses surveyed said everyone travelled in the same
class, regardless of their position, but in most organisations the
recognition of status had survived the recession. Nearly 60 per cent said
status in the organisation dictated class of travel.
Those who travel first class and stay in the best hotels have only a hazy
notion of how their travel is organised. Most of the details are handled by
secretaries.
Nearly two thirds of the secretaries influence their company's choice of
travel agent. One senior manager said: 'I've got secretaries who will sit
there and say 'I don't want to use these people' and then we won't use them.
It's as simple as that.'
Another executive said: 'My secretary organises it all. She will ensure I
get whatever I want at whatever time I want it.'
More than 80 per cent of travellers relied on secretaries to check their
travel details, yet only 7 per cent of the secretaries said their bosses
regularly returned with a gift. Half said they had never received anything.
</TEXT>
