FT  05 NOV 92 / Tecs put forward plans for redundant mineworkers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIX TRAINING and Enterprise Councils in areas that will be affected by the
first 10 coal-mine closures presented the government yesterday with action
plans designed to help those communities.
Tecs - the employer-led bodies that deliver government training schemes -
have been asked to organise and co-ordinate measures to alleviate
unemployment among former miners. The government has allocated Pounds 75m
for that over the next two years.
It is understood that action plans, which are at an initial stage, contain
proposals for Tecs to work more closely with the Employment Service, which
runs non-training programmes such as Job Clubs.
They will also work in close partnership with British Coal Enterprise, which
since 1984-85 has run counselling workshops, job shops and training
programmes for former miners.
A wider revision of training programmes for the adult unemployed is expected
to be announced by Mrs Gillian Shephard, the employment secretary, after
next week's Autumn Statement.
She has been reviewing all provision including Employment Training and
Employment Action, the work experience scheme. How radical the revision will
be will depend on the department's Public Expenditure Survey settlement.
