<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / TSB to cut 440 jobs in shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TRUSTEE Savings Bank is making 440 managers and clerical staff redundant
as part of a merger of its retail banking and insurance operations. The move
is the latest in a series of attempts by banks to reduce staff costs, John
Gapper writes.
TSB said yesterday that 80 senior managers had already left the bank, mostly
by voluntary redundancy. It hoped to reach agreement on voluntary redundancy
with 150 branch managers over the next few months.
The remaining job losses in TSB Retail Banking and Insurance will involve
120 computer staff and 80 clerical staff. The company, which employs 25,000
staff, said it expected most would leave within a year.
The job losses were criticised by the banking union Bifu, which said it
would hold meetings with members employed by TSB Retail Banking and
Insurance over the next few weeks to decide on how to respond.
Ms Jennifer Cole, a Bifu negotiating officer, said the job cuts were
'totally indefensible' and would damage customer service. The union said it
believed there would be further job losses as a result of the operations
merger.
Ms Cole claimed that surplus staff were being told that if redeployment was
not possible within 28 days, they might be sacked before Christmas. That
claim was denied by the bank, which said there was no set timetable of this
kind.
</TEXT>
