<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the good things about Waiting for God is that, like the sixties
series 'Till Death Us Do Part' and 'Steptoe And Son', it rarely takes the
easy option. It manages to generate laughter while, and even by, dealing
with big and difficult topics. Recently Diana and Tom, two of the more
headstrong inmates of Bayview ('home for the nearly dead') have started
sleeping together, causing deep distaste and outrage among younger people.
Today Diana falls ill, decides she is dying, and asks Tom to get sleeping
pills to help her take matters into her own hands. Is euthanasia funny? If
any programme can make it so this one will (8.30 BBC1).
Rumpole Of The Bailey (9.00 ITV) returned last week with a timely story
about over-keen social workers creating child sex abuse cases by putting
leading questions to children. This week the character who finds plot-lines
overlapping at home and at work is Mr Justice Featherstone (Peter Bowles).
The Channel 4 current affairs series Critical Eye reports on the case of
three ex-members of the Ulster Defence Regiment whose convictions for murder
were quashed on appeal earlier this year (9.00).
</TEXT>
