<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / Accountancy Column: Absent figures that add up to an
incomplete picture - The case for the disclosure of discretionary investment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE LETZA and IAIN WARD-CAMPBELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A BLOW was dealt to the health of the UK economy last week with the latest
financial reporting standard launched by the Accounting Standards Board. The
decision to drop its proposal for the disclosure of discretionary investment
will divert attention from the importance of long-term financial measures
for corporate prospects.
For over two decades the accountancy profession has been continually hounded
by City commentators for the lack of reliability in UK financial reporting.
In times of recession, it becomes an even greater focus of attention as
large numbers of companies fail after reporting seemingly healthy profits.
That suggests the need for reform.
Those who simply argue for greater skill among readers of accounts in
interpreting existing financial information take a defensive position used
over more than 20 years by the accountancy profession and provide little by
way of solutions.
It must be questioned whether in today's globalised, fast-moving and
risk-infested business environment 'the figures speak for themselves'. While
greater knowledge and understanding of accountancy can undoubtedly be
useful, more fundamental questions need to be asked.
Most important is: what is the purpose of accounting? On the one hand,
accounting may be viewed as a process of reporting on the 'stewardship' role
of management. This can be adequately accomplished by the pretty basic
reporting of past financial transactions, most frequently expressed in terms
of the 'historical' monetary exchange which occurred at the time of the
transactions.
Enshrined in law, this approach has the so-called virtues of verifiability
and objectivity. But only a nodding acquaintance with accounting reveals
that this supposedly objective reporting process is shot through with highly
subjective estimates and expressions of opinion.
On the other hand, accounting may be viewed as a much more sophisticated
process of providing information for decision-making. This requires an
altogether more dynamic type of information.
Nowadays, most authoritative commentators, both from business and commerce
and from academia, recognise the interest in and right to corporate
information of a much wider group of parties than merely the owners or
shareholders of a company.
This wider group - the stakeholders - embraces creditors, customers,
employees, the government and society at large. Where stakeholders in a
company have an intimate knowledge of the internal workings of the company,
it can be argued that they have no need for sophisticated accounting
information to be made publicly available. The information necessary to
guide these stakeholders can be obtained elsewhere.
That is certainly the case in a number of countries. In Germany - where
there are less than one-fifth the number of listed companies than in the UK
 -the various stakeholders generally have representation at board level and
have access to information well beyond that contained in the published
accounts. It is therefore not surprising that published financial reports in
Germany fulfil only the basic stewardship reporting function, which is
reflected in their format and contents. 'Decision usefulness' is not a
primary objective.
In the UK a different accounting tradition has developed. The number of
listed companies is far greater and the information needs of users, who tend
not to be party to the internal workings of the company, are far more
extensive. As a result, there is a much greater need for annual reports to
provide users with relevant and reliable information to guide them in their
decision-making. Accounts have decision usefulness as a primary goal.
But if UK published financial statements must attempt both to satisfy
accounting for stewardship and to supply information to help
decision-making, what is being done to provide stakeholders with reliable
and relevant information?
First, there is the degree to which 'comparability' between different
companies' accounts has been improved, and the narrowing of areas of
difference and choice in accounting treatments, which will hopefully reduce
the opportunity for 'creative accounting'.
In recent years, the accounting profession has made considerable progress on
this issue with the formation of the Accounting Standards Board (ASB) and
associated bodies - though not without considerable external application of
the whip and spur. The framework for setting accounting standards is now
much tighter and seems to be operating with much more effective teeth than
the regime it replaced.
Second, there is the issue of the provision to users of information about
long-term, sustainable performance. Analysts and market commentators are
currently viewed as being too preoccupied with quick fix, short-term
measures.
Given the apparent (and widely acknowledged) impossibility of accountants
ever being able to provide a reliable, one-measure figure for earnings, it
does seem rather bizarre that analysts and others should attach so much
importance to it. To be fair, this is an attitude with which business has
seemed at times all too ready to conspire.
What the wider stakeholder needs is additional information on activities
that will lead to long-term sustainable performance rather than short-term
measures. These include research and development, advertising and other
marketing development, personnel development and Total Quality issues.
These are activities which have traditionally been written off by companies,
yet which are clearly investments for future health, as opposed to the
essentially historical financial information which is currently predominant
in accounts.
The need for stakeholders to be able to scrutinise these items of
expenditure is sufficiently important to overrule companies' resistance to
disclose such information.
Several recent research studies have demonstrated a link between some of
these issues and sustainable long-term financial performance. Work carried
out at the Bradford University Management Centre has shown a strong
correlation between use of Total Quality Management (TQM) techniques and
significantly better than industry-average financial performance. The study
showed that 29 companies with TQM programmes were well above the industry
norm over five years for profitability, return on capital employed and
earnings.
Quantification and disclosure of these expenses was one of the features of
the first Financial Reporting Exposure Draft (FRED 1) published by the ASB,
which it called 'discretionary revenue investments'. Unfortunately, the ASB
dropped these proposals in the face of criticism by industry and little
public support, arguably so it could help build support in its campaign to
abolish the much-abused extraordinary item, which was perceived as a more
important concern.
Accountancy is a conservative profession and is notoriously slow to adopt
new attitudes and practices. Under the present system, companies which
invest in anything other than tangible fixed assets in order to achieve
long-term, sustainable performance are to a large extent penalised in the
short-term.
We believe this will continue to be the case until sufficient attention is
given to the identification, measurement and disclosure of these highly
significant and potentially desirable investments by business. The present
system can only act to the detriment of the long-term health of our economy.
Steve Letza is lecturer and lain Ward-Campbell Provident Financial Fellow in
Accounting at the University of Bradford Management Centre
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 14
</PAGE>
