<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / Community seeks companies' skills, not cash: Chris Tighe
reports from a disadvantaged North Shields estate that wants business on
tap, not on top
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WINDOWS of the Cedarwood drop-in centre on North Shields' Meadowell
estate are stained white from anti-graffiti solvent and clouded with damp
from the washing spinning in the machine in an adjacent corridor.
The handleless door of the meeting room has to be held shut to prevent an
invasion of shrieking toddlers, but the concentration of the senior
businessmen inside is unbroken.
With a combined annual turnover totalling many billions of pounds, they went
last week to the Meadowell estate at the invitation of Prince Charles,
Business in the Community's president, to discover the corporate benefits
and practical difficulties of business involvement with the community.
The Tyneside visit was one of 16 'Seeing is Believing' trips run this year
by BIC, founded to encourage companies to make community involvement an
integral part of successful business practice. Many trips take high-flying
executives to deprived areas they would never otherwise see.
The visit to the Meadowell estate, scene of riots last September, was
amiable, not confrontational. Some executives chuckled when Mrs Kath
Thompson, one of the residents doggedly working to improve the estate,
smilingly suggested a model for companies' involvement in the community: 'on
tap, not on top'.
They murmured assent when the visit's leader - Mr Richard Maudslay, managing
director of Rolls-Royce's Industrial Power Group - spoke of businesspeople's
fear that community involvement just means being asked for money.
Mr Maudslay's message, echoed throughout the trip, was that business has
much else, in skills, resources, knowhow and influence, to contribute to the
community.
A variation on that theme came from the Rev David Peel, the Cedarwood
Centre's project leader: 'You can do things to people, for people or with
people; we try to do things with people.'
BIC trips are rich in contrasts. Among the visitors to south Meadowell's
streets of boarded-up, vandalised houses was Mr Henry Clarke, deputy chief
executive of The Crown Estate, which includes such upmarket addresses as
Pall Mall and St James's in London.
Treasury deputy secretary Mr Michael Scholar, responsible for the pay and
conditions of 580,000 civil servants, listened attentively as a local
employer explained the 'benefits trap', which makes some residents poorer if
they take a job.
Mr Maudslay spoke of the 'terrible culture clash' when executives, keyed up
by recession and redundancies to make every minute count, tried to cope with
unstructured meetings attended by unemployed people with endless time. The
visitors, who will report back to Prince Charles at a seminar next month,
left Meadowell thoughtful but not despairing.
The enthusiasm of residents such as Mrs Thompson impressed many.
Mr Mark Higson, operations director of Courtaulds subsidiary International
Paint, said: 'I'm fairly shocked by the state of Meadowell but I'm very
struck by the idea (that) business needs to offer practical help, not a
cheque book.'
Several believed that lack of work was the root of Meadowell's ills.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 13
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-9523</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKEB7AF0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921105
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / Minister visits closure-threat London hospitals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT decisions on closures of London hospitals are likely to be
completed about the end of January, Dr Brian Mawhinney, health minister,
said yesterday.
Dr Mawhinney has this week begun visiting all hospitals identified for
closure or change in Sir Bernard Tomlinson's report into London healthcare
published last month.
He began on Tuesday at St Thomas' - which the report recommends should
amalgamate on a single site with Guy's - and yesterday visited University
College and Middlesex hospitals. The report recommends that these should be
rationalised with other specialist services on the University College site.
Dr Mawhinney said his visits would enable managers and staff to raise any
points they wished about the Tomlinson report's proposals, which would lead
to a reduction of about 2,500 hospital beds in London.
One of his next visits will be to St Bartholomew's, where a campaign has
been launched against a recommendation to close the 800-year-old hospital.
The government has emphasised that the Tomlinson recommendations are not
government policy, and says decisions on any closures will be made only
after Dr Mawhinney completes his programme of visits.
Ministers recognise, however, that it will then be necessary to act quickly
and end the uncertainty over threatened hospitals.
A disproportionate level of London's health resources is spent on hospital
services, and the Tomlinson report argues for a shift towards the capital's
relatively underdeveloped general practitioner and community services.
Many National Health Service staff are concerned that, at a time of acute
public-spending constraints, money released by hospital closures might not
be reinvested in better services at community level.
Dr Mawhinney said London, with 15 per cent of the national population,
consumed 20 per cent of healthcare resources. He did not think any minister
could give an 'unqualified guarantee' that its ratio would remain inviolate.
</TEXT>
