<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / Woolwich launches loan aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WOOLWICH Building Society launched two schemes yesterday to help up to 1.5m
people who have mortgage debts that exceed the value of their homes.
A further fall in the Halifax building society's house-price index meanwhile
confirmed the continued downward trend in UK house prices.
One scheme offered by Woolwich, the country's fourth largest building
society, would allow people to use equity in their homes as security for
part of their children's new mortgage. The other scheme allows borrowers to
transfer their existing mortgage, including the negative equity element, to
a new home of the same or lower value.
Mr John Wriglesworth, housing analyst at UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, said the first
scheme was the most innovative homes initiative so far.
Mr Gary Marsh, house price specialist at Halifax, said: 'The pattern of
1992, of seasonally adjusted falls of 1 per cent every month, shows every
sign of continuing.' Halifax is calling on the government to lower base
rates by at least 2 percentage points to 6 per cent and to introduce
measures, aimed particularly at first-time buyers, to stabilise house prices
next year.
Last month's 1.2 per cent fall in the index - 0.8 per cent after seasonal
adjustment - follows a fall of 3.1 per cent in September, or 2.9 per cent on
a seasonally adjusted basis. The index indicates a fall of 8.7 per cent in
the past year.
These developments increase pressure on the government to address the
decline in the housing market in its Autumn Statement next week.
The Halifax index comes a day after Nationwide's house-price index recorded
a fall of 2.7 per cent last month, after a 1.4 per cent fall in September.
Mr Wriglesworth said: 'The two indices have come into line over the
two-month period.' He attributed the sharp fall during the two months to the
ending of stamp duty relief and expects house prices to be down by at least
a further 5 per cent next year.
Mr Peter Lyon, global strategist at Smith New Court, said the continued fall
in house prices showed that monetary policy was still too tight. Interest
rates would have to be reduced significantly to initiate recovery, he said.
He did not expect house prices to rise in real terms for five years.
In Scotland, the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors said yesterday
that the main concern of prospective buyers was job security. Recent
interest rate cuts had not spurred people into moving home.
Scotland has not suffered mortgage repossessions on the same scale as
England, the institution said, but many areas report static prices and slow
turnover. Mortgage lending was 'disappointing' in the third quarter of the
year, according to the Council of Mortgage Lenders yesterday. At the end of
September, outstanding loans for house purchases totalled Pounds 336.3bn, up
from Pounds 330.1bn in the previous quarter and 6.6 per cent higher than for
the third quarter last year.
</TEXT>
