<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / Maxwell's Death - The First Anniversary: Family comes to
terms with shifting fortunes - A year on at the surviving members of the
Maxwell dynasty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS and RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE will be a poignant reminder of the Maxwell family's shifting fortunes
in the run-up to Christmas with two Sotheby's auctions of the contents of
Headington Hill Hall - the Maxwell family home in Oxford.
The sales - organised by administrators to Robert Maxwell's personal estate
 -will include wine, paintings and an assortment of memorabilia.
The combined sales are expected to raise about Pounds 1m - none of which is
likely to end up in the hands of the family, although Mrs Betty Maxwell, the
tycoon's widow, is arguing for a share of the proceeds. The auctions will be
followed within months by the sale of the remainder of the Maxwell lease on
Headington Hill Hall, which belongs to Oxford City Council. The lease is
being sold by PHL Estates, a private Maxwell company under administration.
Mrs Maxwell is not destitute. She still owns a large chateau, reportedly
valued at Pounds 3m, in Lot et Garonne in France, which she has firmly told
administrators belongs to her. She has provided Pounds 900,000 to cover the
legal fees of her sons.
In January she surfaced briefly to sue the magazine Paris Match for
publishing photographs of her husband's autopsy. She has refused to give any
interviews since earlier in the year but is preparing a book of memoirs.
By contrast Mrs Pandora Maxwell, Mr Kevin Maxwell's wife and Robert
Maxwell's least favourite daughter-in-law, has put forward an image of
family resilience in a series of public declarations.
'The only image my children have of prison,' she said recently, 'is when
they went to see the Wind in the Willows and saw Toad languishing in jail.
They hero-worship their daddy. The pressure is enormous . . . '
Her husband has kept both his sense of humour and equanimity in spite of the
criminal charges he faces. He is negotiating a publishing contract for a
book on the effects of bankruptcy. There will be only one chapter on his own
experience.
Kevin and his brother Ian - who also faces criminal charges - abandoned an
attempt earlier this year to set up a Dollars 10m media investment fund.
Kevin, who subsequently signed up briefly as unemployed, decided to take
himself off the register and seek work as a consultant. He and his brother
Ian have moved into an office in central London.
In an affidavit sworn after his father's death, Kevin valued his assets at
Pounds 1.6m and admitted to debts of Pounds 1.75m. Over the past year he has
sold his London home and his Morgan car. He and his wife live in her
converted barn in Oxfordshire and their three children go to a local private
school - with fees, estimated at between Pounds 2,900 and Pounds 5,000 a
term, being paid by relatives.
Investigators have established that five days before the death of her
father-in-law Mrs Pandora Maxwell sold Munday Dean, a racehorse she owned,
at the Newmarket sales for 14,000 guineas. Bankruptcy trustees are meanwhile
dicussing the 26,000 Irish guineas proceeds of a second horse, Great Max,
earlier this year.
Mr Ian Maxwell still lives in the Belgravia house he occupied at the time of
his father's death, but he is losing a FFr2.5m chateau in France he owned
with Kevin and their respective wives. Bankruptcy trustees are preparing to
put it up for sale.
</TEXT>
