<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / Gummer makes secret visit
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John Gummer, agriculture secretary, flew secretly to Chicago on Tuesday
in a vain attempt to help break the deadlock in the talks on farm trade and
the Uruguay Round.
Mr Gummer, who was in the US on church business, registered under an assumed
name at a hotel near the Mayfair Regent Hotel where EC and US officials were
holding talks.
He took no part in the negotiations, which Brussels handles for the EC, but
was there to strengthen the hand of Mr Ray MacSharry, the EC agriculture
commissioner. The UK currently holds the EC presidency and Mr Gummer chairs
this council.
Mr Gummer's surprise appearance came as Mr Ed Madigan, US agriculture
secretary, is understood to have told Mr MacSharry that dealing with the EC
was like 'negotiating with phantoms' because each country had a different
line. The US claimed that Mr MacSharry was going beyond his mandate, or that
he could deliver more within it.
Mr MacSharry dialled Mr Gummer's room and said ask the president of the
council 'if I'm being inflexible'. Mr Gummer duly gave his backing. The US
came up with a compromise, but the talks later collapsed.
