   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NIPPON Mining, the Japanese metal processing and oil refining group,
yesterday reported a 36.5 per cent slide to Y3.06bn (Dollars 25m) in parent
company pre-tax profits in the half-year to September from Y4.81bn a year
earlier, as a result of weak demand and prices throughout its core
businesses.
Sales fell by 11.7 per cent to Y384.84bn from Y435.72bn.
In the metals side of the business, sales fell by Y13.9bn to Y141.1bn, with
sales of copper, gold, and silver all reduced in value. The volume of zinc
sales fell, although a rise in prices helped improve the value of sales.
The volume of petroleum products sales fell from 8.69m kilolitres to 8.16
kilolitres, while the value of sales was off by Y39.45bn to Y241.26bn.
At the net level, Nippon Mining's profits fell by 64.5 per cent to Y905m
from Y2.55bn.
