<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / The Maastricht Vote: Time on ministers' side over Euro-bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Government's narrow escape means the Maastricht ratification process
will continue.
As ministers breathed again, however, it was evident that urgency was the
last thing on their mind.
In his winding-up speech to the Commons, Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign
secretary, made clear that the government believes there is 'a reasonable
chance' that December's Edinburgh summit will agree a package for Denmark.
At the same time, language to harden the definition of subsidiarity - the
passing down of decision-making to the lowest appropriate tier of government
 -is also expected to be hammered out.
If that goes according to plan and the Danish parliament approves a second
referendum, a new plebiscite could be held by May.
Mr Hurd implicitly made clear, however, that both issues might run into
snags. But that is a Community concern and Britain should have at least
three months to complete the committee stage and reach a third reading.
In the short term, the British government's efforts to press on with
ratification will be merely symbolic - a goodwill gesture of good faith to
offer its Community colleagues at the Edinburgh gathering.
Ministers and business managers have hinted that as little as two days of
the committee stage will probably be held before December 12.
After the summit, there might be a couple more committee days before the
Christmas recess.
But as the government plans to achieve its goal of ratification by
attrition, the real slog will not begin until the Commons returns in the new
year.
One government minister indicated yesterday that the initial plan is to
allow the normal processes to run their course.
Labour will harry the government with ambushes, intent on maximising
disruption to its legislative programme.
There is a wide belief, though, that the filibuster that it is anticipated
will be launched by the Tory Euro-sceptics will soon tire the clear majority
around the house who favour early nights and long weekends.
Furthermore, aware that the Labour leadership will eventually call for
abstention on the final vote, the opposition taste for the fight will
diminish, too.
'If people start finding that a bunch of single-issue fanatics are beginning
to interfere with their chances to take advantage of their daughter's
half-term from school, then opinion will harden against them,' the minister
said.
Nonetheless, it is plain that many of the fiercest 'oppositionists' are
planning just that.
Mr Bill Cash, one of the most prominent campaigners, will boast to anyone
ready to listen that he has 250 amendments to the bill already tabled, with
more to come.
If the process goes to March, Mr Cash can expect his personal popularity to
be wearing thin.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9
</PAGE>
