<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / The Maastricht Vote: Major lives on to fight another day -
Philip Stephens reports that last night's vote may prove to be a turning
point for the government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT WAS as nerve-racking as it was dangerous. But Mr John Major lives to
fight another day.
Last night's vote on the Maastricht treaty was his first political success
since sterling's exit from the exchange rate mechanism threw his government
into crisis on September 16. It marked a step along the road to
rehabilitation.
Even so, there are plenty of obstacles still to be cleared.
The prime minister's confidence, drained by the collapse of his economic
policy on Black Wednesday and by a succession of political miscalculations
subsequently, has received a significant boost. He gambled his political
future on Europe. He won, albeit by a hair's breadth.
His performance in yesterday's debate was one of his strongest since the
general election. He nodded frequently in the direction of the soft
Euro-sceptics - offering reassurances that there would be no single
currency, no common defence policy, no cession of control over immigration.
But his strongest and most important message was the one central to the
debate: Britain has a choice whether to remain at the centre of events in
Europe or slink away to the fringes.
What Mr Major is inclined to describe as a struggle for the soul of the Tory
party has not been settled conclusively. The Euro-sceptics are a resilient
bunch.
But enough in his party realised as they trooped through the Commons
division lobbies at 10pm last night that there was nothing to be gained from
destroying the prime minister. His premiership has lost the brief magic that
accompanied his April general election victory. For the moment, though, his
party has decided it has nowhere else to go.
Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, is a serious loser. He judged that to hold
his party together he had to lead them into the lobbies against the
government. But Labour's Europeanism has been tarnished. Attacks on the
Liberal Democrats for their support for Mr Major will not soothe the his own
party's obvious discomfort.
If Mr Major heeds the advice of elder statesmen such as Lord Whitelaw he
will now tread carefully, seeking to rebuild his authority on the Tory back
benches with calm self-confidence rather than with unnecessary
confrontations. In the metaphor of one experienced backbench Tory, his
government must stop putting padlocks on fire exits and then throwing away
the key. Flexibility is occasionally a sign of strength.
Mr Major has won the point on Europe. With Labour unlikely to oppose the
legislation in the substantive debates that will follow, the Euro-sceptics
have lost their best chance to wreck the ratification process.
So the prime minister can go to next month's Edinburgh summit with tangible
evidence that he is true to his word.
His European partners will have seen his political problems, but if they
still hold hopes for Maastricht it will be in their interest to help rather
than hinder him.
His priority now must be the economy. The disgruntlement on his back benches
reflects more than anything else the government's failure to deliver
economic recovery. The reality rather than the empty promise of an end to
the recession could transform the political landscape.
The prime minister must convince his own supporters - and the country at
large - that he can construct an economic policy which will deliver that
recovery.
It will not be easy. The cabinet bargaining on the share-out of the Pounds
244.5bn public-spending cake for next year has been less than edifying.
The limited resources in the Treasury's contingency reserve have been more
than absorbed by higher spending on unemployment-related benefits, on EC
farm spending, on the expansion of tertiary education and on a sharp
increase in legal aid.
Everyone else is facing a sharp reduction in previously agreed budgets. They
are warning of dire consequences inside and outside Westminster.
The council tax bills that will land on doormats in the south of England
next spring threaten a political explosion comparable to that over the
government's ill-fated coal closures plan. In spite of the promise of some
creative accounting, the final decisions across all Whitehall programmes
will be harsher than expected.
It will take considerable sleight of hand to dress up a freeze or sharp
restriction on public-sector pay, large job losses in defence-related
industries, and a squeeze on state benefits as an Autumn Statement for
recovery.
So the accompanying package of measures will have to be convincing.
An interest rate cut is regarded on the Conservative backbenches as a sine
qua non. But there will have to be other measures of substance - to boost
the construction industry, to steady consumer confidence - if the
government's supporters are to be convinced the spending cuts are a price
worth paying.
Last night Mr Major could raise his head and smile for the first time in
nearly two months. It might prove a turning point for a government that has
looked hell-bent on self-destruction. But the House of Commons did not write
the prime minister a blank cheque. For now, all he can claim is a line of
credit.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
