<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / The Maastricht Vote: Appeals to support government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
APPEALS TO wavering rebels to support the government came from senior Tory
backbenchers on both sides of the argument, though the moves to rally
backbenchers also contained warnings for ministers about their conduct of
the UK presidency of the Community, Alison Smith writes.
The message from the few hardline Tory Euro-sceptics who spoke in the debate
was defiant, however. Mr Michael Carttiss, the Tory MP for Great Yarmouth,
said he was going to vote both against the Labour amendment and the
government motion.
He said unless the prime minister established a coherent economic programme,
he risked going 'the same way as George Bush, only quicker. This Maastricht
Bill is a monstrous irrelevance to the real issues that face this government
and the country.'
Sir Edward Heath, the former prime minister who took the UK into the EC,
urged potential rebels to recognise that, in previous cases where the Tory
party had been divided, such as Suez, dissidents had held back from
endangering the government.
Mr Paul Channon, a former cabinet minister, professed himself sceptical on
the Maastricht treaty but argued that Tories should support the government
to strengthen its hand in negotiating to achieve a decentralised EC. 'It
would have saved us all a great deal of trouble if the French had voted
against it,' he said.
</TEXT>
