</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / The Maastricht Vote: Ashdown berated for relief of besieged
PM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR leaders accused Mr Paddy Ashdown and his Liberal Democrat followers
of providing a lifeboat for Mr John Major, the prime minister, in the
Commons last night, when the government survived two crucial votes on the
Maastricht treaty by majorities of three and six.
In tumultuous scenes in the crowded chamber, Mr John Smith and his
colleagues on the Labour front bench knew they were on the wrong end of a
see-sawing debate seconds before the result was officially announced.
Mr Ashdown took the brunt of the verbal assaults unleashed by Labour MPs as
soon as the emergence of Mr Richard Ryder, the government chief whip, from
behind the speaker's chair signalled that the government had successfully
survived the first vote with a majority of six.
The insults directed at the Liberal Democrats who voted with Mr Major and
his supporters in both divisions became even more abusive when it was
announced that the main government motion had been carried by a majority of
only three.
In a bitter comment after the hubbub subsided, Mr Jack Straw, Labour's
shadow environment secretary, charged Mr Ashdown and his party with
betraying the millions of people who voted for them in April's general
election. 'The only thing the Liberals have been true to is their colours -
yellow,' he said.
An unrepentant Mr Ashdown renewed his charge that it was Mr John Smith who
had abandoned his principles by refusing to support the government and
sullying his record as a consistent supporter of Britain's membership of the
European Community.
Earlier the Labour leader had insisted that the ambiguous and anodyne
government motion had more to do with the internal crisis in the
Conservative party than with the EC and the Maastricht treaty.
In a vigorous defence of Mr Smith at the close of the debate Mr John
Cunningham, shadow foreign secretary, said the prime objective of the main
motion was to re-establish the authority 'of an increasingly accident-prone
and embattled prime minister trying to establish his authority over his
increasingly querulous party'.
Labour would not assist in that objective, he said, and in a pointed thrust
at the Liberals warned 'those who do will be required to account for their
actions to an angry and incredulous British public'.
Mr Smith highlighted the sharply contrasting indications from government
quarters in recent weeks about the importance that ministers attached to the
debate.
He emphasised that a briefing by Downing Street officials had led to
newspaper reports that a government defeat would result in Mr Major calling
a general election.
Scoffing at the navety of Liberal Democrat MPs, he said they had been
'conned by the Conservatives'.
Mr Smith said that for Labour MPs to adopt the same course would amount to
an endorsement of the government's decision to opt out from the social
chapter - 'that might suit the Liberal Democrats but it would be a betrayal
for us'.
Mr Smith argued that further proceedings on the bill should be delayed until
after the Edinburgh summit in December, when the terms secured by the Danish
government for staging a second referendum on the Maastricht treaty would be
clarified.
He contended that a statement made by the the prime minister in September
amounted to an acceptance that the 'framework' for the second Danish
referendum would have to be agreed at the Edinburgh summit before MPs were
asked to deal with the next stage of the bill.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
