<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / The Maastricht Vote: Government a mere two votes away from
defeat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE narrowness of the government victory last night is highlighted by a
breakdown of the results.
If an extra two Tories had switched sides and voted against the government
on its motion, or a handful more had abstained, Mr Major would be
contemplating defeat this morning.
Both the Labour and Conservative parties achieved a full turnout of members
 -267 and 332 MPs respectively. In the first vote - on Labour's amendment to
the government motion - there were 10 abstentions by Tory MPs and 23 who
voted against the government.
But in the second vote, on the government's motion, three more Conservative
MPs - Mr David Porter (Waveney), Mr Michael Lord (Suffolk Central) and Mr
John Carlisle (Luton North) - joined the Conservative rebellion.
In addition there were seven abstentions, cutting the government majority to
just three.
Four speakers and deputy speakers, plus the two tellers for each side, do
not count in the final voting figures. A total of 319 members voted for the
government motion to proceed with ratification. They included 299
Conservatives, 19 Liberal Democrats and one Ulster Populist Unionist MP. A
total of 316 members voted against the government motion, consisting of 267
Labour, 26 Conservatives, one Liberal Democrat, four SDLP, three Scottish
Nationalists, four Welsh Nationalists, eight Ulster Unionists and three
Democratic Unionists. The 26 Tories who voted against the government motion
were Mr John Biffen (Shropshire N), Sir Richard Body (Holland with Boston),
Mr Nicholas Budgen (Woverhampton SW), Mr John Butcher (Coventry SW), Mr John
Carlisle (Luton N), Mr Bill Cash (Stafford), Dr Michael Clark (Rochford), Mr
James Cran (Beverley), Mr Iain Duncan-Smith (Chingford), Mr Christopher Gill
(Ludlow), Mrs Teresa Gorman (Billericay), Mr Toby Jessel (Twickenham), Mr
Roger Knapman (Stroud), Mr Barry Legg (Milton Keynes SW), Mr Michael Lord
(Suffolk C), Mr Tony Marlow (Northampton N), Mr David Porter (Waveney), Mr
Richard Shepherd (Aldridge Brownhills), Sir Trevor Skeet (Bedfordshire N),
Mr Michael Spicer (Worcestershire S), Sir Peter Tapsell (Lindsey E), Sir
Teddy Taylor (Southend E), Mr Bill Walker (Tayside N), Mr John Wilkinson
(Ruislip Northwood), Mrs Ann Winterton (Congleton), Mr Nicholas Winterton
(Macclesfield).
</TEXT>
