<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 92 / Government will proceed with bill to curb unions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT, in an unexpected move, will today publish and give first
reading to a bill imposing further curbs on trade unions. It will include
the right of citizens to take out injunctions against unlawful strikes.
The bill is also expected to pave the way for the abolition of wages
councils, the statutory bodies that set pay rates for more than 2.5m workers
in low-paid jobs. Mr Michael Forsythe, the employment minister, said in the
Commons this week that the government saw no permanent place for wages
councils.
Mrs Gillian Shephard, the employment secretary, said last week that the
bill, expected to be brought forward this autumn, was being postponed on
technical grounds until later in the year.
The bill lost its parliamentary slot but Conservative party business
managers have now squeezed it into the timetable.
The legislation, on which Tory MPs are united, could be a morale booster to
a party divided on other issues.
In addition, the government may feel it wants to be sure of the new powers
relating to strikes and public services before the full impact is felt of
any pay squeeze in the public sector.
The bill, whose architect was Mr Michael Howard, the environment secretary
and former employment secretary, is expected to conform broadly to its
original form.
It will include the right of employers to regularly seek employees' consent
for union dues to be deducted from pay on automatic 'check-off'. That is
expected to adversely affect union funds, which are already under pressure.
Unions will also have to give seven days' notice of strikes and individuals
will have the right to join the trade union of their choice regardless of
the Trades Union Congress arrangement for regulating inter-union disputes.
The green paper received a lukewarm reception from employers' organisations,
including the Confederation of British Industry.
</TEXT>
