<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / Survey of Northern Greece (10): Thessaloniki looks to 1997 -
Blocked overland routes have cut the number of foreign tourists
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR YEARS, northern Greece seemed to lack both of the essential components
of Greek tourism: impressive archaeological remains and a range of
spectacular beaches.
The region's main attraction for foreigners was the theocratic republic of
Mount Athos, where Orthodox monks offer ascetic hospitality and keep a
strict ban on women.
Quite suddenly, both ruins and beaches were discovered. The excavation in
1977 of the tomb of King Philip of Macedon, Alexander the Great's father, at
Vergina, put northern Greece firmly on the archaeological map. The tomb's
glittering contents - from jewellery and gold-decorated armour to silver
drinking cups and ivory miniatures - can capture the attention of even the
most reluctant museum-goer.
At the same time, the Halkikidi district was opened up for mass tourism,
with a new road around the remote Sithonia peninsula, giving access to
dozens of sandy beaches. With 18,000 hotel beds and a motorway link with
Thessaloniki, Halkidiki is now the package holiday centre for the north of
the country.
However, the violent break-up of Yugoslavia, the route to Greece for
tourists driving from central Europe, has brought problems. Despite a marked
increase in charter flights to Thessaloniki, tourist arrivals dropped by 37
per cent in the first eight months of 1992.
'We used to have Germans and Austrians driving down to Halkidiki, but now
it's Hungarians and Czechs coming by bus and car through Bulgaria. They
can't afford the same standard of holiday,' says Mr Vassilios Brovas,
chairman of the Thessaloniki Hoteliers' Federation.
The flow of Yugoslav visitors from Belgrade and weekend shoppers from
Skopje, amounting to over 1.2m arrivals in 1989, has also dried up.
Smaller hotels in Thessaloniki and Halkidiki have suffered most from the
tourist slump, with average occupancy rates dropping to only 43 per cent.
The big hotels, with occupancy still above 60 per cent, can rely on the
city's commercial attractions to bring in business.
More than 1.5m visitors, both Greeks and foreigners, attend the half-dozen
big trade fairs staged every year at Thessaloniki's international exhibition
centre. Conference tourism is also on the rise, extending the season - two
months shorter than in the rest of Greece - by several weeks in spring and
autumn.
For the moment, hotels in Thessaloniki can combine their facilities to
handle conferences of up to 2,000 people. That will change after 1995, when
a new congress hall is due to open at the exhibition centre, with capacity
for 8,000 delegates.
But the year already inked in on every hotelier's calendar is 1997, when
Thessaloniki becomes the European City of Culture. The city's first major
facelift in almost a century is already under way. Its centrepiece is a
Dr65bn (Pounds 200m) project to build an underground railway through the
city centre, to reduce traffic congestion.
Although the timetable will be tight, after a long dispute over finding a
site, city officials are still confident that a new Dr17bn concert hall can
be built in time for 1997.
Meanwhile, the city's unique collection of Byzantine churches, some still
shrouded in scaffolding following an earthquake 15 years ago, is being
spruced up, so that frescoes and mosaics will be on view again. A new
Byzantine museum, displaying artefacts from all over northern Greece is due
to open next year.
In Halkidiki, hoteliers have turned to the international tour operators,
accepting low room rates in return for guaranteed arrivals this season. The
number of arrivals by charter flights to Thessaloniki rose by 50 per cent
this summer, bringing over 200,000 tourists from northern Europe.
'Increased charter flights to Thessaloniki are an encouraging sign that
Macedonia can be a place that people choose to come to, rather than just
pass through says Mr Thomas Gudantsis, National Tourist Organisation
director for Macedonia and Thrace.
The expansion of passenger shipping in the northern Aegean is also bringing
more tourists to Macedonia. Along with regular ferry connections to Piraeus
and the southern islands, a hydrofoil service now links Thessaloniki with
the Sporades islands, off central Greece.
The city can now cater for two categories of sought-after tourists:
passengers on cruise ships and on yachts, who spend much more freely than
the package holidaymakers. A new passenger terminal at Thessaloniki port has
encouraged cruise ships to make more regular calls, offering excursions
around the city and to Vergina. The city marina has at last been completed,
offering facilities for yachts in a still uncrowded part of the
Mediterranean.
Nevertheless, Macedonia's loss has been Epirus's gain in terms of tourist
arrivals, with drivers taking a ferry from Italy to north-western Greece in
order to avoid the former Yugoslavia. Epirus is still one of the
least-visited regions of Greece, though it is not short of antiquities set
in dramatic mountain scenery.
Ioannina, the provincial capital, which is set on a lake, was a favourite
stopover for 19th century tourists who liked to call on Ali Pasha, its
hospitable but unpredictable ruler. A sizeable collection of Ottoman-era
buildings survives inside the fortifications of the old castle - from which
Ali Pasha's enemies were thrown into the lake - along with his summer
retreat on a reed-fringed island.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI
