<DATE>921104
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / Survey of Northern Greece (9): They can't afford to quarrel
 -Businessmen are attracted by Bulgaria's new market economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT TAKES five hours to drive from Thessaloniki to Athens, but only three to
reach Sofia, the Bulgarian capital.
That is one reason why northern Greek businessmen are enthusiastic about
working in Bulgaria, despite their concerns about the lack of a clear legal
framework for foreign investment and property ownership.
To circumvent these problems, Greeks are going into partnership with
Bulgarians. Over 200 Greek-Bulgarian joint ventures have been established
since Bulgaria started its transition to a market economy.
'The joint ventures cover a very wide range of activities, from retail and
marketing to consultancy and manufacturing, though this is developing rather
slowly,' says Mr Emmanuel Vlahogiannis, treasurer of the Thessaloniki
Chamber of Commerce and Industry.
'Bulgaria is an attractive market for Greece, being about the same size and
in need of the kind of consumer goods that we can provide. Their development
is going to be rather like ours in the 1950s and 60s.'
Fast-moving consumer goods are the mainstay of the Greek retail trade in
Bulgaria. Coffee, chocolate, ice-cream, jeans and training shoes are the
most popular items, according to Greek exporters.
A scramble is on to find business premises in Sofia, preferably in a
building that has already been restored to its original owners - to avoid
the possibility of being summarily evicted if the property changes hands.
There appears to be little difficulty in converting payments in Bulgarian
lev into US dollars, which are handed over in cash at Bulgarian banks, but
there can be problems with arranging a transfer to a Greek bank in
Thessaloniki.
'You can't just drive home with a briefcase of dollars in the boot. It took
me months to organise payments through the banking system, because Bulgarian
banks aren't geared up for sending money out of the country. But now I can
get a transfer through in one week,' says Mr Apostolos Genitsaris, whose
activities in Bulgaria extend from setting up an ice-cream distribution
network to trading in oil and petroleum products.
However, the free-wheeling climate of Greek-Bulgarian trade is starting to
change, following a Bulgarian decision to impose a 30 per cent import tariff
and set up a quota system for a wide range of goods.
Business on the Greek side of the border consists mainly of Bulgarians
arriving to shop at a large Greek supermarket just over the frontier. Some
Bulgarians come as far as Kavalla or Thessaloniki in search of spare parts
or a service for their car.
It is hoped that dealings with Bulgaria will happen on a more organised
footing once the new Greek-Bulgarian Chamber of Commerce starts operating,
probably early next year. Meanwhile, seven medium-sized Greek towns close to
the Bulgarian border are promoting commercial links with four others in
southern Bulgaria under the European Community's Interreg programme for
cross-border co-operation.
Greek affiliates of international accounting and consultancy companies are
participating in the EC's Phare programmes for assisting Bulgarian economic
development. They also seem keen to get involved in Bulgaria's privatisation
programme as financial advisers.
'There may soon be enough work available for us in Bulgaria to justify
opening an office there,' says Mr Yiangos Charalambous, a partner at KPMG
Peat Marwick Kyriacou, which earlier this year carried out an audit for the
new American-funded university at Blagoevgrad in southern Bulgaria.
But several Thessaloniki-based manufacturing companies have postponed plans
to set up plants in Bulgaria, because of the difficulties of acquiring a
greenfield site. Under current Bulgarian law, foreigners are allowed to buy
buildings but can only lease land.
Meanwhile, four fast-growing Athens-based companies are already establishing
themselves in Bulgaria. Hellenic Bottling, which holds the Coca-Cola
franchise for Greece and Ireland, has launched a Dollars 18m joint venture
to produce Coca-Cola and other soft drinks at five Bulgarian bottling
plants. Delta Dairy, a food processor, is setting up an ice-cream plant at
Varna, a Black Sea resort.
Intracom, a telecommunications company, is negotiating the sale of a
computerised lottery game to the Bulgarian state. The Vardinoyannis group,
with oil and banking interests, has opened the first in what is planned as a
network of petrol stations in Bulgaria, to be supplied from its refinery in
Greece.
However, the business environment for Greek companies in Bulgaria is to some
extent clouded by a distinct coolness in the two countries' political
relations.
The Greek government was angered by Bulgaria's decision to recognise the
former Yugoslav republic of Macedonia earlier this year, though this was
somewhat mitigated by a Bulgarian decision not to send an ambassador to
Sofia until the EC approves recognition of the newly independent republic.
Greek politicians are unhappy about the Bulgarian government's dependence on
parliamentary support from the country's ethnic Turkish party. Before the
collapse of communism, Greece and Bulgaria - though members of opposing
alliances - found common cause in their mutual suspicion of Turkey.
It does not help that talks have stalled in a long-running dispute over how
much water the Bulgarians are entitled to pump out of the river Nestos
before it reaches Greece. The Bulgarians, for their part, are upset that
their requests for new border crossings into Greece to be opened up, and for
access to the port of Alexandroupolis in Thrace, only 30 miles from the
Bulgarian frontier, have not yet been granted.
But given the threat of increased political instability in the southern
Balkans, Greece and Bulgaria cannot afford to start quarrelling.
'If there is real trouble in ex-Yugoslav Macedonia, the road through
Bulgaria will be Greece's only overland link to western Europe. Obviously,
they need each other,' says a western diplomat.
</TEXT>
