<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / Survey of Northern Greece (7): Migrants readily find jobs -
Epirus: Albanians continue to flood across the frontier
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LEAN, weatherbeaten men tramping the roads of Epirus, their possessions
kept in a cloth bag slung over one shoulder, are immigrants from Albania.
They can be seen at any hour of day or night, travelling in twos and threes
to look for work.
The trickle of Albanians crossing the border in north-western Greece has
turned into a flood over the past year. There are thought to be over 200,000
Albanians - about 6 per cent of the country's population - in Greece. Among
them are former diplomats and university professors. But an overwhelming
majority are young men who enter Epirus illegally across the mountainous
border.
As part of its commitment to improve relations with Albania's democratic
government, Greece has adopted an attitude of laissez faire tolerance
towards the immigrants, who do not ask to be treated as refugees.
In fact, it would require draconian measures to keep them out. Greek
commandos patrol the border, but villagers on the Albanian side make a
living out of guiding immigrants to out-of-the-way footpaths leading into
Greece.
A senior police officer in Ioannina, the provincial capital, says: 'Most
days, we pick up about 500 Albanians in Epirus who don't have valid visas in
their passports, and bus them back to the border. But there are probably
more than that number coming across.'
Greece issues visas to Albanians of Greek descent, most of them
Greek-speakers from the North Epirus region of southern Albania, adjoining
north-western Greece. Over 40,000 North Epirots and their families are now
legitimate residents. In addition, Greece has agreed with the democratic
government in Tirana to accept another 30,000 Albanians as short-term
migrant workers.
It says something about the size of the black economy in Greece that
Albanian immigrants have little trouble in finding jobs, however temporary.
Albanians are in much demand as casual workers in agriculture and
construction, as they will accept a daily wage of Dr3,000 (Pounds 9). While
this is less than half the basic rate for Greeks, it is equivalent to almost
a month's salary in Albania.
The flow of arrivals looking for seasonal work increased dramatically after
Albania's democratic government launched a tough economic reform programme
in July, in return for a stand-by loan from the World Bank, freeing food
prices and cutting unemployment benefits.
It is clear that the plight of the impoverished North Epirots, cut off from
Greece during Albania's 40 years of Stalinist self-isolation, touches Greek
sensibilities.
Although there are few organised reception facilities for them, North
Epirots use a network of extended family contacts in Greece to find
better-paid jobs in the service sector. They are given preference over other
unskilled workers applying for work, and employers are more willing to help
ease them into the legal economy by meeting their social security
obligations.
Inevitably, the impact of the Albanian migration is felt most strongly in
Ioannina. Thousands of Albanians have settled in the city, which is only a
two-hour bus ride from Argyrokastro, the nearest big Albanian town - where
most transactions are now carried out Greek drachmas rather than Albanian
lek.
Ioannina is where returning migrants buy up household appliances, food
supplies and (increasingly) second-hand cars, to take home. Several thousand
refrigerators, television sets and washing machines are taken across the
border every week, according to Greek customs officials.
'The shops do well, but there are social problems. The Albanians have a
tradition of violence, and we have much-increased rates of crime and
prostitution,' says a provincial official.
With the aim of slowing the immigration rate, the Greek government is
preparing a medium-term aid and development programme, to be focused on
southern Albania.
It is awaiting approval, by the Group of 24 western industrialised
countries, of a Dollars 75m plan for setting up agro-industries in Albania,
from chicken-farming and pig-raising to canneries and the launch of a
fishing fleet.
'Informal and disorganised as it may be, the Albanian immigrants are getting
valuable exposure to a free-market system. That experience will be important
in making their own economic transition,' says a Greek official.
The government has also extended its incentive scheme for promoting
investment in remote regions of Greece to southern Albania, offering grant
aid and tax concessions even for small-scale projects.
However, the complex bureaucracy inherited from the communist past, together
with the slow pace of decision-making in Tirana, seem daunting to Greek
businessmen.
'The public administration is still in very weak shape, and there are doubts
about the legality of property transfers. You can sign a protocol, but there
is no guarantee it will lead anywhere,' says Mr Costas Aslanides, a Greek
contractor who wants to modernise a hotel in southern Albania.
In the meantime, a government-sponsored organisation, the Foundation for
Returning Greeks, is shipping European Community food aid to Albania. Truck
convoys leave the Epirus port of Preveza several times a week, carrying
flour to state bakeries in Albanian towns.
Greece itself will provide Dollars 35m in aid to Albania this year, largely
to meet specific requests from the Albanians for a variety of essentials,
from potatoes and pasta to light bulbs and soap.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page V
</PAGE>
