<PROFILE>_AN-CKEBPAEQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921104
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / Survey of Northern Greece (4): Farther to go, more to pay -
War in the former Yugoslavia has made exporting complicated
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ROAD from Greece to western Europe has grown longer and more hazardous
since war broke out in the former Yugoslavia. In recent months, political
roadblocks raised by the UN embargo on trade with Serbia have added to
exporters' problems of rising costs and uncertain delivery dates.
The difficulties are most acute for companies in northern Greece, which
account for just over 50 per cent of total Greek exports valued at Dollars
6.8bn last year.
The region's highest-earning exports are fresh fruit - citrus in winter and
cherries, peaches and grapes in summer - together with yarn and textiles.
Exporters in Thessaloniki note that for both categories, timely delivery,
with no loss of quality on the road, is crucial to remaining competitive.
During 12 years of European Community membership, Greek exports to the
Community have risen from 38 per cent to 65 per cent of total exports. Yet
Greece is at a considerable disadvantage, compared with the other
Mediterranean EC members, because of the extra distance its goods must
travel. It takes almost 24 hours by ferry to cross the Adriatic to southern
Italy, the nearest EC market, and just as long to reach Germany, the biggest
market for Greek exports.
'Now the choice is between an expensive route by ship to Italy or a
time-consuming route through Bulgaria, Romania and Hungary,' says Mr Jordan
Adamidis, director of the Exporters' Association of Northern Greece.
A recent study by the association forecasts that exporters in Macedonia and
Thrace will face losses of up to Dollars 500m this year, as a result of
higher transport costs and lost trade with Serbia and Montenegro.
Textile exporters have fared worst, with average transport costs soaring by
43 per cent. Some manufacturers are resorting to air freight to ship their
goods, while others use the overland route through Bulgaria.
Many food exporters have switched to the Italian route, with costs rising on
average by 29 per cent, according to the study. However, fruit exporters
complain that at peak periods there is not enough capacity for refrigerated
trucks on the ferries serving western Greek ports.
The pressure of increased truck traffic this year during the tourist season
underlined the need for extra quay space and better customs facilities at
ports like Patras, the main crossing point for Italy, and Igoumenitsa to the
north. The government has announced plans for upgrading both ports with the
help of the EC regional fund, but work will not start before 1993.
According to Greek truck drivers and freight forwarders, the alternative
route through eastern Europe is fraught with danger. Roads in Bulgaria and
Romania are narrow and badly maintained, while unwary drivers who pull over
for a nap may wake up to find their load has been stolen.
Further along the route, transit fees through Hungary for TIR trucks have
risen sharply, while Hungarian regulations restrict loads to 20 tonnes
rather than the usual 25 tonnes.
'It's a nuisance, because it adds another 20 per cent to your costs, but
there isn't an alternative route,' says Mr Michael Mistakidis, who exports
rice to central Europe.
The exporters' problems grew worse in July, with the UN embargo on trade
with Serbia and Montenegro. Although overall trade with Greece declined as
the Yugoslav federation started to disintegrate, the southern republics
continued to import Greek fruit and vegetables, textiles and consumer goods
after Slovenia and Croatia broke away last year. Greek exports to Yugoslavia
in 1991, with Serbia much the largest customer, were valued at Dollars 160m,
down from Dollars 180m the previous year.
'Food processors say they've lost 90 per cent of their trade with former
Yugoslavia. The trade in fresh produce has been almost wiped out, because of
the embargo,' Mr Adamidis says.
Even before the embargo was imposed, a well-established trading relationship
with the former Yugoslav republic of Macedonia, adjoining northern Greece,
had been upset by the dispute over what the newly independent should call
itself.
Greek objections to having a country named Macedonia on the doorstep of its
own province of the same name have affected bilateral trade almost as much
as the new state's worsening economic problems. But the situation was
exacerbated by complaints from Greece's EC partners over the summer that oil
sold by Greek companies to ex-Yugoslav Macedonia was being passed on to
Serbia.
Greece is the main supplier of both crude oil and refined products to the
neighbouring republic, in normal circumstances shipping about 120,000 tonnes
monthly by road and rail to a refinery near Skopje.
The Greek government banned local companies from selling oil to its
neighbour, pending the introduction of a new system of import licensing
designed to make sanction-breaking more difficult.
However, another dispute erupted over what ex-Yugoslav Macedonia should be
called on the new import documents. After weeks of acrimonious discussion in
the EC, a compromise solution permits the new state to use the name
Macedonia on its own documents.
The decision will allow more goods to start moving into Skopje, but the
noisy protests from the Greek government suggest that politics will continue
to obstruct exports for some time to come.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-9657</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKEBPAEPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921104
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / Survey of Northern Greece (5): Planners hope for EC
assistance - The government sees Thessaloniki as a transit centre for the
Balkans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TAKE ONE look at a map of the Balkans, and the potential role of
Thessaloniki as a hub for trade and communications becomes clear.
The city is an obvious outlet to the Mediterranean for the former
Yugoslavia, Romania and Bulgaria. It also sits astride what could become the
main land transport route from Italy to Turkey.
The break-up of Yugoslavia has had mixed consequences for Thessaloniki. On
one hand, a lively exchange of goods and services was slowed by the outbreak
of war and, since July, virtually halted as a result of the UN embargo
against Serbia - an important trading partner for Greece.
On the other, Serbia's loss of access to the Adriatic ports of Koper and
Rijeka, now in the independent republics of Slovenia and Croatia
respectively, should mean that under normal conditions Thessaloniki could
expect to handle much of Serbia's international trade.
That, at any rate, is the view of the Greek government, now revising its
infrastructure development policy for northern Greece. The premise is that
Thessaloniki can become a transit centre for the Balkans, resuming a role it
played most successfully in the Byzantine period.
There is a sense of urgency in the air, because much of the funding must be
approved by Greece's European Community partners this year. Greece hopes to
get up to Dollars 14bn in EC assistance from 1993 to 1998 under the second
Delors package for improving infrastructure in poorer EC member countries.
Thessaloniki Port Authority, one of Greece's profitable state-controlled
enterprises, with earnings of over Dr1bn (Pounds 3m) annually, has already
launched its own Dr30bn development plan. Its later stages are to be
included in the new EC funding.
'Our contribution to the development plan amounts to self-financing, because
we don't have to ask for allocations from the public investment budget,'
says Mr John Marinides, director of the port's free zone.
Last year, dry cargo traffic through Thessaloniki totalled 6.5m tonnes. The
projection for 1992 is 7.2m tonnes. Despite the loss of Serbian shipments,
dry cargo traffic through Thessaloniki port was up by 15 per cent in the
first seven months of this year. Oil shipments, which totalled 7.5m tonnes
in 1991, rose by 11 per cent in the same period, Mr Marinides said.
The port's chronic labour problems have eased somewhat in the past year.
Although the 1,000 stevedores still work only one daily shift, with overtime
considered a built-in part of the wage scale, the container terminal now
operates around the clock. Container traffic soared in the first eight
months of 1992.
Cargoes from Romania and Bulgaria have increased, as Thessaloniki becomes a
transshipment centre for both countries. Their exporters are no longer
required to use the facilities of state-owned enterprises, whether railways,
transport agencies or ports, or to follow designated itineraries imposed by
the government.
The development plan for Thessaloniki port aims at doubling capacity for
receiving overland cargoes, adding new warehouses to store bulky and heavy
cargoes and building a new Dr600m railway terminal for handling freight
close to the quayside. The main pier for handling container shipments is to
be extended. Dredging operations will deepen the harbour to 14 metres so
that larger vessels can be handled. A Dr5.2bn earthfill operation will
create additional space for warehouses. Nine new gantry and mobile cranes
will be installed.
'By the end of the decade we should be able to cater for up to 4,000 ships
and handle 9m tonnes of dry cargo a year,' said Mr Marinides.
The EC is also expected to continue funding a highway-building programme
launched in the 1980s. Thessaloniki is the only city in Greece to boast a
dual-carriageway ring road, opened last year, together with a highway to
Halkidiki, the main northern Greek resort area, 100km from the city.
'There's an orgy of road-building going on. There are so many years of
neglect to be made up for,' says Mr George Misaelides, secretary general for
infrastructure projects in central Macedonia.
The challenge for the government is to secure EC approval for completion of
the Egnatia highway, named after the imperial Roman road that crossed the
Balkans from Durres in Albania to Thessaloniki and Istanbul.
The revised route would start at Igoumenitsa, a small western Greek port due
to be upgraded as a ferry terminal for truck traffic. Scattered sections of
the highway already exist, constructed in the haphazard way of past
governments anxious to secure votes through funding small-scale public works
in carefully selected districts.
Thessaloniki airport, used by more than 1.5m passengers a year but still
lacking a runway that can handle wide-body jets, is also in need of
attention. There are daily flights to a dozen western European cities, but
only rudimentary aircraft-parking and maintenance facilities.
However, the most far-reaching plan for exploiting Thessaloniki's position
will involve much more than physical infrastructure. An EC-financed study is
under way, to examine the possibility of basing a Balkan trade centre and
mercantile exchange in the city.
Trade originating in the Balkan countries amounted to Dollars 82.3bn in
1989. But only Dollars 16.9bn of that amount passed through Greece, while
Greece's own trade with the Balkan countries totalled just Dollars 1.6bn.
'The Balkan countries are going to be producing substantial amounts of
low-value added goods for some time to come. Finding markets for them would
be much easier through an exchange forum in the region,' says Mr Costas
Mitropoulos, of Kantor Management Consultants, who are preparing the study.
While financial services in Thessaloniki are improving fast, with almost 30
Greek and foreign banks in the city, it would take a sizeable effort of
political will to establish a regulatory framework and a system for handling
transactions generated by an international exchange centre.
Much will depend on how quickly political stability and economic reforms
take root in the region, allowing the Balkan countries to join the
international trading system without the hindrances of bilateral agreements
and foreign exchange shortages. Greece, for its part, can set an example by
eliminating the politically-inspired bureaucracy that, in the communist era,
significantly hampered the growth of trade with its Balkan neighbours.
</TEXT>
