<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / Survey of Northern Greece (2): EC membership lifts
prosperity - Agriculture: about a third of Greek output now comes from the
north
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FARMING IN northern Greece is now a business rather than a way of life.
Holdings are larger, crops more varied and mechanisation more extensive than
in the south of the country.
Farmers' incomes are high, in some places rivalling those of Cretan
vegetable-growers, the wealthiest Greek producers.
Almost 12 years of European Community membership has brought a dramatic rise
in Greek farmers' standard of living. About two-thirds of EC transfers,
amounting to over Dollars 17bn since Greek accession, have gone to support
prices for agricultural products. For most crops, even the withdrawal prices
provide farmers with a comfortable living.
About one-third of Greek agricultural output now comes from northern Greece,
with production concentrated in the plains of Macedonia. Northern farmers
grow 62 per cent of cereals, 50 per cent of maize and 80 per cent of sugar
beet produced in Greece.
In addition, about 55 per cent of the tobacco crop comes from the north.
Irrigation is well-advanced: the region also specialises in growing cotton,
to supply the local yarn and textile industry, and is one of the few
rice-producing areas in the EC.
Over the past decade, fruit-growing on the hillsides above the Macedonian
plains has developed into a major commercial activity. Apples and pears are
grown for domestic consumption, while peaches, pears and cherries have
become high-earning exports.
'Farmers in this region are professional in their outlook, despite the
relatively small size of their holdings. They're willing to change crops,
and they're susceptible to new ideas about machinery, because they work the
land themselves,' says Mr Nikos Efthymiades, of K&amp;N Efthymiades, Greece's
leading agrochemicals manufacturer.
Agriculture has not always flourished in this part of Greece. Farming
remained a subsistence occupation, even after the population exchange
between Greece and Turkey in 1922 had brought thousands of skilled farmers
to the region from Asia Minor. The newcomers were granted what were fairly
large landholdings by Greek standards, averaging about 10 acres, as former
Turkish-owned properties were handed over and big estates were broken up.
But it was only after the completion of large-scale anti-flood and drainage
programmes, carried out with government funding and US expertise, that
output started to increase significantly. Another 300,000 acres of
cultivable land became available, mainly in fertile river valleys in
Macedonia and Thrace.
Tobacco is still the traditional crop in Thrace, although the oriental
varieties, suited to the district's poorer soil, face a steady decline in
demand. Macedonian farmers are taking over, growing more Virginia tobacco,
which commands much better prices. Younger farmers in Thrace are starting to
give up tobacco, switching to cotton and wheat instead.
The picture is rather different in Epirus, a much more mountainous region.
In the valleys and coastal plains, olive and citrus cultivation remain the
main agricultural activities. In the mountains, sheep-raising is still
important, and considerable amounts of cheese are produced by traditional
methods.
However, the main growth area in all the northern Greek provinces is dairy
production. Output has grown rapidly since the early 1980s in response to
sharply rising consumer demand. As a result, large Greek milk and yoghurt
producers compete in providing incentives for farmers to keep small herds of
dairy cows.
These include extending loans to farmers to buy Dutch and French cows,
providing veterinary back-up, and help in getting EC subsidies to build
cowsheds. Some companies take Greek dairy farmers to Holland for seminars in
animal husbandry.
Demand for sheep and goat's milk is also high, with the shepherds of Epirus
able to claim payment three or four months in advance for their winter and
spring milk production.
Milk output in Greece now totals 1.78m tonnes yearly, of which 694,000
tonnes is produced by cows, 640,000 tonnes by sheep and 462,000 tonnes by
goats. Most sheep and goat milk is used for cheese-making, with only a small
percentage used for yoghurt.
'Demand for cow's milk is still increasing at the rate of about 5 per cent
yearly, and there is probably some way to go, since canned evaporated milk
still covers about 40 per cent of the market. Per capita consumption of
fresh milk in Greece is still less than half the the EC average,' says Mr
Thanassis Kravas, marketing director of Mevgal, a milk and yoghurt producer
near Thessaloniki.
Although small family-run dairies continue to make sheep's yoghurt, about
three-quarters of Greek yoghurt output, amounting to around 77,000 tonnes
annually, is now factory- produced. Exports have risen from 2,000 tonnes in
1987 to 7,500 tonnes last year, with sales concentrated in Britain France
and Italy.
However, surpluses of other farm products are showing an increase. This
year, more than half of a record peach crop, reaching over 920,000 tonnes,
was dumped. Greece is one of the world's largest producers of canned
peaches, with 90 per cent of industrial peaches grown in western Macedonia.
But canning capacity, at only 250,000 tonnes, has failed to keep pace with
the growth in production.
Citrus output is also heavily in surplus, partly because Greek oranges are
mainly old-fashioned varieties which cannot compete in EC markets with
Spanish or Israeli produce. At the same time, demand from eastern European
countries, which used to buy large quantities of Greek citrus under
bilateral government-to-government trade agreements, has shrunk in the past
two years.
One reason for the rising surpluses is that Greek farmers receive
comparatively little support or advice from the state agricultural extension
service. Until recently, seed production and sales were a state monopoly,
with the result that research and development of new seed varieties has
lagged behind the rest of Europe. At the other end of the production cycle,
marketing and exporting of Greek produce is in need of better co-ordination.
From next year, farmers face a sizeable drop in product prices under the
revised EC agricultural policy. Support rates for both marketed produce and
withdrawals will start declining at a time when costs are increasing.
Fertiliser prices have soared since the government lifted all remaining
price controls earlier this year.
Mr Alkis Giziades, who farms 20 acres of his own land outside Thessaloniki
and another 15 acres of rented property, sums up the farmer's dilemma:
'Fertiliser prices have tripled in less than a year, and diesel is up by 30
per cent. Wheat and cotton prices will be down by 10 per cent at least. That
makes you wonder whether you should plant less and switch to milk - even
though feed's gone up and cows are hard work to look after.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page II
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-9659</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKEBPAENFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921104
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / Survey of Northern Greece (3): Non-investors lose ground -
Textiles are the largest export, but a two-tier industry is developing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A STROLL down one of Thessaloniki's main shopping streets reveals the
strength of the local textile and clothing industry. Boutiques displaying
imported labels are vastly outnumbered by windows filled with Greek-made
fabrics and garments.
From the automated weaving plants of large manufacturers in countryside
towns to the basement workshops in Thessaloniki's poorer neighbourhoods, the
industry employs more than 40 per cent of Macedonia's workforce. Over 4,000
companies, about one-third of the industry total, are based in the region.
Production is strongly export-oriented, with over 70 per cent of local
companies selling abroad. Germany is much the largest market for both
fabrics and ready-wear.
'Northern Greek companies cannot compete on price with the Asian
garment-makers. But they are well placed to carry out smaller 'repeat'
orders for big German traders, having acquired a reputation for good
quality-control and punctuality in meeting delivery dates,' says Mr Rigas
Tzelepoglou, a Thessaloniki-based management consultant.
Greece's textile industry developed rapidly from the 1970s, thanks to
increased output of locally grown cotton and low labour costs. Import
tariffs, together with substantial export subsidies, provided an additional
stimulus for expansion.
Northern Greece attracted textile companies keen to take advantage of
government incentives for industrial investment outside Athens, as well as
the lower cost of labour in the north of the country, while transport from
Thessaloniki for companies exporting to northern Europe was also cheaper at
that time.
After joining the European Community, Greece was no longer subject to quotas
for textile exports; but, on the other hand, was obliged to phase out both
tariffs and the export subsidy system that had kept less efficient
manufacturers comfortably afloat. Meanwhile, competitiveness started to
erode as labour costs moved steadily higher.
Textiles are still Greece's largest export, earning Dollars 1.8bn last year.
But a two-tier industry has emerged, with a widening gulf between successful
companies, maintaining competitiveness through continuous investment, and
manufacturers who are rapidly losing ground through their inability to renew
machinery and equipment.
'We've gone from a labour-intensive to a capital-intensive business. To
compete, you have to renovate equipment, organise better and keep on
improving quality and customer service,' says Mr Christos Accas, managing
director of Hellenic Fabrics, the largest Greek textile group with annual
turnover of Dr30bn (Pounds 97.3m).
Unlike most Greek textile companies, the group is both vertically and
horizontally integrated, running a cotton-ginning plant near Thessaloniki
and manufacturing yarns, fabric and garments. Its largest unit is an
integrated spinning and weaving mill, which produces denim for the jeans
industry, mainly for export.
'There is still room for expansion: after all, we produce one of the best
cottons. But it's hard to keep reducing production costs, and the industry
as a whole is gradually losing competitiveness. There are going to be big
problems in the future,' Mr Accas says.
According to some analysts, up to 50 per cent of Greek textile producers and
garment-makers are likely to go out of business over the next few years.
Competition from the eastern European countries is expected to grow, with
new spinning and weaving mills being set up to take advantage of cheap
labour and proximity to the German market.
Yet garment-makers are likely to be hardest-hit. Three-quarters of Greek
ready-wear manufacturing is done by small family units with five or fewer
employees. There are only 24 companies that employ more than 200 workers.
The focus on small-scale production based on imported patterns gave little
scope for developing Greek-produced designs. As a result, Greek
garment-makers have been unable to create products with brand names or build
sales networks abroad.
Until recently, the flexibility of small producers enabled them to keep on
winning orders from abroad. But rising costs and aggressive competition from
Spain and Turkey are making things difficult at a time when domestic demand
is shrinking. For the moment, companies in Thessaloniki, where some 40 per
cent of Greek garment-makers are based, seem to be holding on to customers
more successfully than in the south of the country, according to local
exporters.
However, the industry now faces an additional problem as a result of the
government's efforts to tighten exchange-rate policy, pegging the drachma
more firmly to the Deutsche Mark and slowing the depreciation rate against
other European currencies.
'Devaluation of the peseta and the lira is going to have adverse effects on
our competitiveness. The export market has been getting more difficult, and
now the drachma is overvalued by at least 10 per cent,' says Mr George
Athanassiades, of Hellenic Pella Mills, a yarn-producer.
With spinning mills facing slackening demand for ordinary cotton yarns, Mr
Athanassiades has switched to making yarns that combine cotton with acrylic
and polyester fibres, and coloured yarns. He says his company has spent
Dr650m on new investment in the past three years, mostly out of its own
funds.
Mr Athanassiades has also diversified into importing, becoming the agent for
Adidas shoes and athletic wear in Greece. He says: 'Continuous investment is
important in this business, If you slip behind, you can't meet demand for
better quality. But it's also important to reduce risk - and sales of brand
name products in Greece are healthy.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page II
</PAGE>
