<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / International Company News: Royal Trust down CDollars 243m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROYAL TRUST, the Canadian financial services group, hopes to shake off
financial problems which have dogged it in recent years with a package of
measures which include a deep dividend cut, an equity issue and a special
loan-loss reserve.
The Toronto-based company said all its operations, with the exception of
those in the UK, were profitable.
But write-downs on discontinued operations and the new bad-debt provision
pushed the company to a third-quarter loss of CDollars 243m (USDollars
195m), or CDollars 1.68 a share, compared with earnings of CDollars 33m, or
10 cents, a year earlier.
Royal Trust's share price closed down more than 15 per cent to CDollars 3.60
on the Toronto stock exchange yesterday.
Its problems stem mainly from a disastrous expansion outside Canada in the
late 1980s, including the acquisition of Dow Chemical's financial services
arm and the purchase of a string of US west coast savings and loan
institutions.
The Seattle-based S&amp;Ls, brought together under Pacific First Bank, were sold
last week for CDollars 663m.
Third-quarter earnings include a write-down of CDollars 73m on the
investment in Pacific First. However, Royal said the sale would strengthen
its capital base by CDollars 195m, lifting its capital-to-assets ratio from
9.4 per cent to 12 per cent.
The quarterly dividend has been halved to 5 cents a share and the board has
approved a CDollars 200m equity issue. Terms will be announced later, but
Royal said its controlling shareholder, Trilon Financial, had agreed to take
up its share.
