<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / Ministers fail to agree on 2% pay rise ceiling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH, PHILIP STEPHENS and CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OUTLINE of the package of economic measures to be announced in next
week's Autumn Statement was agreed by Mr John Major yesterday as cabinet
battles over next year's Pounds 244.5bn public spending total looked set to
continue right up to the weekend.
After a meeting of almost two hours yesterday morning, ministers said a
cabinet struggle over public sector pay remained unresolved, with some
ministers still pressing for a total freeze rather than a 2 per cent ceiling
on rises, to free more resources for capital programmes.
The cabinet will meet again tomorrow, but some senior ministers signalled
that they expected to have to continue the discussions on Friday.
Tomorrow's meeting is likely to be given an indication of the economic
measures to be announced with the Autumn Statement, including rule changes
on private sector financing of capital projects.
As ministers began going through each department's spending programme, Mr
Michael Howard, the environment secretary, was said by colleagues to be
fighting hard to defend his Pounds 2bn-a-year budget for housing
associations, pointing to a manifesto commitment to the associations'
housebuilding programme.
He warned the cabinet separately that too tight a squeeze on overall local
authority spending would threaten a backbench revolt when the House of
Commons votes on the arrangements for the council tax in January.
Plans by EDX, the cabinet committee on public spending, to impose deep cuts
on the defence budget hit strong opposition from Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the
defence secretary.
In what a Whitehall insider described as one of a series of 'moving
speeches' around the cabinet table, Mr Rifkind is said to have warned of the
loss of thousands of jobs. Some defence-dependent companies might also be
threatened.
Others arguing strongly for increased allocations were Mrs Virginia
Bottomley, the health secretary, and Mrs Gillian Shephard, the employment
secretary.
Mrs Shephard is understood to be pressing for next week's statement to show
the government launching a drive to boost industry. This would put the
emphasis not only on capital projects, but also on her department's training
and employment programmes.
Unemployment and the pay of public sector workers were two of the central
concerns raised with Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, in a meeting with
representatives from the Trades Union Congress.
After the discussion - the first official, bilateral meeting between the
chancellor and the TUC since the early 1980s - Mr Norman Willis, general
secretary of the TUC, said union leaders told Mr Lamont that things were
'awful out there'.
'We told him that the government must tackle jobs and we must have a
recovery, and he listened carefully,' Mr Willis said.
In the 80-minute meeting, the union leaders presented their plan for
economic recovery, and warned Mr Lamont it would be 'morally unacceptable'
for Britain's lowest paid workers to be hit by a pay freeze. The
government's plans to hold down public sector pay were challenged yesterday
with the announcement of a 4.9 per cent pay increase for Britain's 42,000
firefighters.
The Local Government Management Board, which negotiates on behalf of local
authorities, described the 12-month deal as the last of this year's public
sector pay round.
The government, however, is likely to see it as among the first of next
year's wage agreements, and thus a test of its resolve on public sector pay
rises.
</TEXT>
