<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Unless today's episode of The Secret Agent shows signs within the first few
minutes of speeding up, many viewers will surely desert. The first of the
three episodes was perilously slow, but at least Verloc was finally given
his mission (to blow up the Greenwich observatory) and can now set about
manipulating Stevie, his wife's cerebrally challenged younger brother. The
trouble with Conrad's bitter little tale is that when he wrote it, before
the first World War, bomb-throwing anarchists were a significant political
consideration (9.25 BBC2).
More speed might not go amiss either in Pole To Pole, the series in which
Michael Palin is travelling the world from top to bottom. Today he goes from
Istanbul to Aswan on the Nile, meeting astrologer Patric Walker (who files
his copy to the London papers from a Greek island) and the British garrison
in Akrotiri (9.35 BBC1).
The documentary series The Kennedys reached JFK's death at the end of the
last episode and is now poised to move on to Bobby (10.40 ITV). Cool Hand
Luke is a memorable chain-gang movie for several reasons, not least the
opening sequence (12.20 ITV).
</TEXT>
