<HEADLINE>
FT  04 NOV 92 / Senior Tories join property bill revolt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TORY backbenchers strongly attacked the government in the Commons last night
for failing to ensure adequate compensation for leasehold property owners
who may be forced to sell their freeholds to tenants.
Mr Jerry Wiggin, MP for Weston-super-Mare and a former junior defence
minister joined with Labour MPs in voting against the Housing and Urban
Development Bill. It was given a second reading by a government majority of
68 (327-259).
Earlier, Mr Michael Jopling, chief whip in the first Thatcher administration
and a former minister of agriculture, protested that many Tory backbenchers
were 'astonished that this government, of all governments, should be seeking
to force people to sell their property'.
Mr David Hunt, Welsh secretary, who wound up the debate, held out little
hope of significant changes being made to the bill.
The likelihood of sustained attempts by Tory backbenchers to secure more
generous treatment for freehold owners during the bill's committee stage was
acknowledged by Mr Michael Howard, environment secretary.
Mr Jopling, MP for Westmoreland and Lonsdale, dismissed as 'nothing of the
sort' government claims that the freehold of such properties would be
acquired by leaseholders at a fair market price.
He told Mr Howard that the bill gave 'great offence to very many of us'.
Mr Wiggin complained that the bill would provide substantial benefit to
leaseholders at the expense of freeholders.
He said a more appropriate title for the move would be the 'Building
Societies (Robin Hood) Bill'.
Mr Howard insisted that the fair compensation provisions in the bill did not
warrant such criticism.
Refusing to accept Mr Jopling's 'strictures', he said it was impossible to
reform property law without affecting existing interests.
Mr Howard told critics of the bill: 'What is important is that interests
which are so affected should be the subject of proper compensation. I
contend that the bill provides for compensation.'
He said up to 750,000 tenants of leasehold flats and houses would have the
opportunity to buy their freeholds.
Mr Jack Straw, Labour's shadow environment secretary, condemned the
government for not including a single line in the bill for building a single
home at a time when there were record homeless people.
Mr Straw said inclusion in the bill of a 'rent to mortgages' scheme when
thousands of owner-occupiers were having their properties repossessed
underscored the government's failure to address the real needs of the
nation.
Mr Michael Alison, Conservative MP for Selby and parliamentary spokesman for
the Church Commissioners, warned that the bill would effectively drive them
and other similar charities out of their traditional housing role in
residential property investment and management.
</TEXT>
